                                Report abuseTranscript of Gregory VII and Innocent IIIGregory VII and Innocent IIIReviewHeight of Papal Power - developing into the most powerful institutions in western ChristendomActions TakenFirst synod (1074) Internal CleansingConflict with Henry IVHenry IV called a synod at Worms (1076) - anathematized GregoryThe CrusadesFeudal WarfareTwo-Swords theory"Donation of Constantine"The Pornocarcy (882-964)Cluniac ReformCollege of Cardinals (1059)Gregory VII (1073)Reforming the Christian ChurchInternal Cleansing of the ChurchFreeing the Church from secular powerAny cleric guilty of simony or fornication was to be removedParishioners were to reject clergy guilty of such crimesRoman synod (1075) Lay investitureClerics who receive offices from laymen will not be recognizedLaymen who invest these offices will be excommunicatedAttacking the problem at the rootGregory excommunicated Henry, deposing him as emperorHenry's public penance (1077)Henry summons a council of bishops - deposed Gregory1080 Henry re-excommunicated; Henry marches on RomeGregory dies in exile (1085)Resolution - not until 1122, Concordat of WormsIslamic control of the Holy LandPope Urban IISpeech at Claremont (1095)Exaggerated Muslim atrocitiesIssued first indulgenceInitiated the First Crusade (1096-99)Love for God and Love for NeighborLove for GodImitating Christ"Bear your cross"Love for NeighborBrothers and friends vs. servants of the Devil and enemies of God"Just Violence" - AugustineThe CrusadesTimelineFirst crusade (1096-99)Captured JerusalemCounty of EdessaPrincipality of AntiochCounty of TripolisKingdom of JerusalemSecond Crusade (1147-48)Muslims Capture Edessa in 1144Antioch was in dangerFailed - Antioch was also lostMeanwhile, in the south the Christians tried to secure EgyptThird Crusade (1189-93)Saladin Captured Jerusalem (1187)Led by Richard "The Lion-Hearted"Philip AugustusFrederick Barbarossa- Drowned- Went back to France- Unable to take JerusalemFourth Crusade (1201-04)Instigated by Pope Innocent IIILed by Boniface of MontferratNever made it to the Holy LandPlundered Constantinople; Baldwin IX made emperorAlbigensian Crusade (1209-29)Against Heretics - CatharsLed by Arnauld-Amalric, Abbot of CiteauxMassacre at BeziersChildren's Crusade (1212)French and German ChildrenMissionary CrusadeDidn't leave the shores of the MediterraneanFifth Crusade (1217-21)Tried to retake the Holy Land through EgyptSpanish Cardinal Pelagius - If you can't beat 'em, convert 'em!FailedSixth Crusade (1227-29)Led by Frederick II - Stupor MundiSultan al-Kamil Frederick became ill - was excommunicatedPope Gregory IX...twiceBogus crusadeBogus treaty (1229)Frederick crowned himself Emperor1244 Jerusalem is overtaken by the Turks againSeventh Crusade (1248-70)King Louis IX of FranceAlliance with the MongolsWent to Egypt - sent back in 1250Jerusalem taken by Mongols in 1260Later that same year reclaimed by the Muslims Louis took the crusade to Tunisia (1270)Succumbed to the plague Full transcriptMore presentations by
    
        
